\begin_layout Section
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
What are nongenetic effects and why do they evolve?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nongenetic effects refer to phenotypic effects in descendants that are brought
 about by the transmission of factors other than sequences of DNA from parents
 or more remote ancestors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bonduriansky2009,Day2011,Jablonka2009,Danchin2011"

\end_inset

.
 Underlying mechanisms include the transmission of DNA-methylation and histone
 methylation variants 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Greer2012,Heard2014"

\end_inset

, small RNAs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Liebers2014"

\end_inset

, maternal hormones 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Groothuis2008"

\end_inset

 and antibodies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hasselquist2009"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far, most research on nongenetic effects has focused on the molecular
 mechanisms underlying nongenetic effects (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Heard2014,Rechavi2014,Rechavi2014a"

\end_inset

).
 Much less thought has been given to questions at the ultimate level, such
 as the evolutionary orgins of these nongenetic effects 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Uller2008"

\end_inset

 and when and where these nongenetic effects may be selectively advantageous.
 However, this has all changed with the advent of a series of recent theoretical
 studies, which have profided the field with a number of predictions about
 the ecological contexts in which nongenetic effects are favored 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kuijper2014a,Kuijper2015,Leimar2015,English2015"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Prediction 1: heterogenous, autocorrelated environments favor nongenetic
 effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These novel models predict that nongenetic effects are selectively favored
 in temporally or spatially variable environments, in which selective conditions
 are correlated between subsequent generations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kuijper2014a"

\end_inset

.
 For example, in species with rapid exhaustion of resources due to population
 growth, high levels of nutrition in the parental generation may induce
 high fecundity and hence low levels of nutrition in the next generation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Murdoch2003"

\end_inset

, resulting in a negative environmental correlation between generations.
 As environments are correlated (either positively or negatively), any parental
 cue about the parental environment (transmitted via these nongenetic effects)
 may then be informative to the offspring about the environment that they
 will face 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Uller2008,Shea2011"

\end_inset

.
 Consequently, offspring could then develop an appropriate phenotypic response
 based on this parental information, resulting in a form of transgenerational
 plasticity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Galloway2007,Uller2014a"

\end_inset

.
 In other words, heterogeneous, autocorrelated environments, should favor
 the evolution of parental influences on offspring phenotype determination.
 However, in homogenous environments or those environments lacking any transgene
rational autocorrelation, we should expect the role of nongenetic effects
 to be much more limited.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Prediction 2: the form of nongenetic effect depends on the specific environment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another exciting prediction is that nongenetic effects may vary in the strength
 and direction, dependent on the particular environment.
 For example, recent models on parental effects found that negatively autocorrel
ated environments (i.e., an environment that changes rapidly) should favor
 
\shape italic
negative
\shape default
 nongenetic effects, where offspring phenotypes are more different to their
 parent's phenotype than to the phenotype of a random, unrelated individual
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kuijper2014a,Kuijper2015"

\end_inset

.
 By contrast, in a positively autocorrelated environment (i.e., an environment
 that changes slowly), positive nongenetic effects are favored, where offspring
 phenotypes are more similar to their parent's phenotype relative to the
 phenotype of a random, unrelated individual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently, we not only have a theory that predicts when and where nongenetic
 effects are favored, but also what shape they are likely to take, which
 can be tested using quantitative genetics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Danchin2011"

\end_inset

.
 What is now needed are tests of these predictions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Testing the theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Armed with these theoretical predictions, we now need to device experiments
 that enable us to test whether i) correlated environments indeed favor
 the evolution of nongenetic effects and ii) whether different signs and
 magnitudes of nongenetic effects are favored in different environments.
 Microorganisms such as yeasts provide an ideal platform for this, as their
 genetic architecture is extremely well understood 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kim2010,Botstein2011,Rhind2011,Jeffares2015"

\end_inset

 and they have fast generation time (2h in a benign environment).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Existing studies on adaptation of yeast in fluctuating environments have
 mainly focused on bet-hedging 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Seger1989,Starrfelt2012"

\end_inset

.
 For example, a study by Acar and coworkers on 
\shape italic
Saccharomyces cerevisiae
\shape default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Acar2008"

\end_inset

 showed that some mutants exhibit stochastic phenotype switching, whereby
 descendant phenotypes attain a phenotype opposite to their parents.
 They showed that such mutants are highly advantageous in fluctuating environmen
ts, as the entailing phenotypic heterogeneity enhanced survival prospects
 at the level of the genetic lineage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stochastic phenotype switching studies highlight the potential for transgenerati
onal phenotypic change in yeast.
 However, phenotype switching is not the same as a nongenetic effect.
 Strict definitions of phenotype switching assume that the mixture of offspring
 phenotypes is uncorrelated to the phenotype of the parent 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jong2011"

\end_inset

.
 By contrast, the presence of a nongenetic effect necessarily implies that
 the phenotype of offspring is, in some form, dependent on the phenotype
 of its parent.
 So far, studies of phenotype switching have paid little attention to the
 important notion whether switching rates depend on the parental phenotype.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Questions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
My experiments aim to address the following two questions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Do nongenetic effects exist in fission yeast 
\shape italic
Schizosaccharomyces pombe
\shape default
?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
How much do different strains vary in the propensity for nongenetic effects?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Can stronger or weaker nongenetic effects evolve by means of experimental
 evolution?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model organism: fission yeast
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fission yeast 
\shape italic
Sz.
 pombe
\shape default
 is a model organism that has been classically used for studies on cell
 division and meiosis, as its chromosomal architecture is very similar to
 higher eukaryotes.
 Also, it has a substantial scope for nongenetic effects, as it has extensive
 regions of epigenetically induced chromatin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cam2005,Ragunathan2014,Allshire2015,Audergon2015"

\end_inset

.
 However, most of these heterochromatized regions are restricted to non-coding
 regions (centromeres, telemeres) or regions with very particular biological
 functions (mating type loci).
 Beyond these genomic regions, however, it is poorly understood whether
 nongenetic effects play a more general role in adaptation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suggestions that nongenetic effects may be important in 
\shape italic
Sz.
 pombe
\shape default
 stem from the notion that damaged proteins inherit asymmetrically upon
 cell-division 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Erjavec2008"

\end_inset

, with most of the damaged proteins remaining in the parental cell.
 This shows that cells have the machinery in place to adjust the amount
 of proteins that can be transmitted to the daughter cell.
 In addition, it is well known that severe stress leads cells to produce
 stress granules, which are found in the cytoplasm and contain proteins,
 mRNAs and non-coding RNAs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Anderson2009"

\end_inset

.
 Interestingly, such stress granules have been associated with nongenetic
 inheritance (i.e., maternal inheritance) in multicellular organisms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rajyaguru2009"

\end_inset

, but the inheritance of stress granules in unicellular organisms has seen
 surprisingly little attention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Experiment 1: testing for the presence of nongenetic effects by exposing
 consecutive generations to different environments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Experimental setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I test for the presence of nongenetic effects by inoculating two environments
 
\begin_inset Formula $F0(E1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F0(E2)$
\end_inset

 with cells from the same colony.
 Subsequently, we sample descendant cells from each of these treatments,
 and expose half of these cells to treatment 
\begin_inset Formula $E1$
\end_inset

 and the other half to treatment 
\begin_inset Formula $E2$
\end_inset

, yielding four different combinations of exposure in 
\begin_inset Formula $F0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F1$
\end_inset

 (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:experiment_1"

\end_inset

).
 During the 
\begin_inset Formula $F1$
\end_inset

 treatments, we measure growth rates as a measure of fitness.
 If nongenetic effects would be absent, we would expect that any differences
 in growth rate between 
\begin_inset Formula $E1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E2$
\end_inset

 are independent of the parental environment.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $F1(E1)_{F0(E1)}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $F1$
\end_inset

 exposed to 
\begin_inset Formula $E1$
\end_inset

, parental generation exposed to 
\begin_inset Formula $E1$
\end_inset

) has the same average growth rate as 
\begin_inset Formula $F1(E1)_{F0(E2)}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $F1$
\end_inset

 exposed to 
\begin_inset Formula $E1$
\end_inset

, parental generation exposed to 
\begin_inset Formula $E2$
\end_inset

).
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $F1(E2)_{F0(E1)}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $F1$
\end_inset

 exposed to 
\begin_inset Formula $E2$
\end_inset

, parental generation exposed to 
\begin_inset Formula $E1$
\end_inset

) has the same average growth rate as 
\begin_inset Formula $F1(E2)_{F0(E2)}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $F1$
\end_inset

 exposed to 
\begin_inset Formula $E2$
\end_inset

, parental generation exposed to 
\begin_inset Formula $E2$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Problems with this approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One perceived problem with the current experimental setup is that each environme
nt induces selection, so that cells sampled from the 
\begin_inset Formula $F0(E1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F0(E2)$
\end_inset

 treatments used to inoculate the respective 
\begin_inset Formula $F1(E1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F1(E2)$
\end_inset

 treatments may not be genetically identical.
 As a consequence, differences in growth rates would then be genetic rather
 than nongenetic.
 However, we know that genetic variation in the standard 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{+}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-}$
\end_inset

 strains is generally very low 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jeffares2015"

\end_inset

, thus limiting the response to selection.
 Moreover, as we only use heterothallic strains, asexual reproduction further
 limits an efficient response to selection 
\end_layout

